to declare and limit, to justify and condemn. In examining this fraught, contested, and evolving relationship, Law and War investigates such questions as: What can efforts to subsume war under the logic of law teach us about the aspirations and limits of law? How have paradigms of law and war changed as a result of the contact with new forms of struggle? How has globalization and continuing practices of occupation reframed the relationship between law and war?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aJurisprudence. 0aWar (International law) 0aWar (International law). 4aglobal warfare. 4alaw and war. 4alawfare. 4alimits of the law. 4apolicing war. 4aregulating war. 4arules of warfare. 4aterrorism. 4awar and justice. 4awar crime. 7aLAW / Jurisprudence.2bisacsh1 aDouglas, Lawrence, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSarat, Austin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aUmphrey, Martha Merrill, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804788861zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804788861423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804788861.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles